{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644078"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:02:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:02:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18035"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18035"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.1,0.25,0.5,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73395"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10749"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58861"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"8111"},{"type":"tags","id":"9885"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25103"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73395"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMetastatic spread to lymph nodes in the neck is a well-recognised complication of many different types of cancer. A \u0027sentinel node\u0027 is a phrase used to describe a lymph node that is either visible or palpable and may contain metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following lymph nodes is considered a sentinel node?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Jugulodigastric node","Jugulo-omohyoid node","Submandibular node","Supraclavicular node","Submental node"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe left \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraclavicular node\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Virchow\u0027s node, is considered a sentinel node. It is often associated with metastatic spread from abdominal malignancies, such as gastric cancer (Image). The presence of an enlarged left supraclavicular node can be a significant clinical finding, indicating possible underlying malignancy. The right supraclavicular node is less commonly associated with abdominal malignancies compared to the left side. It may be involved in thoracic or breast malignancies but is not classically referred to as a sentinel node.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ejugulo-omohyoid node\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ejugulodigastric node\u003C/strong\u003E are part of the deep cervical lymph nodes but are not typically referred to as signal nodes. They are more commonly involved in head and neck infections or malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmandibular node\u003C/strong\u003E is situated under the mandible and is not thought of as a sentinel  node.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmental node\u003C/strong\u003E is located under the chin and is involved in drainage from the mouth and lower face. It is not considered a sentinel  node.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sentinel nodes, are the first lymph nodes to which cancer cells are most likely to spread from a primary tumour.","The left supraclavicular node, also known as Virchow\u0027s node, is a classic example of a sentinel node, often associated with abdominal malignancies."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58861"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18035"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21354"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21354"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CQTKWfpUpngzsK97uNeiIuvol354ij.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/CQTKWfpUpngzsK97uNeiIuvol354ij.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":547,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58861"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T14:57:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T14:57:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10749"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73395"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updat